Obviamente, no soy ni crítico ni experto. Pero considero que esta interpretación de Muti debe estar entre las mejores jamás realizadas de la Coral. Observad la ejecución del Allegro: medida, firme, emocional; planteando el leit motiv con una energía convincente, sin apresuramientos ni falsos dramatismos. Ni hablemos del Scherzo: Muti despliega una paleta de recursos expresivos de enorme magnitud, logrando que la sinfónica de Chicago (de por sí un conjunto de músicos de alta excelencia) alcance cotas inusitadas de profundidad, energía y texturas; el conjunto se escucha con una potencia y plasticidad contundentes y, al mismo tiempo, es posible escuchar cada timbre individual. El Adagio... el Adagio es una obra de arte: aquí podemos comprobar la exquisita sensibilidad y gusto de Muti. Sus manos se ralentizan y trazan arcos expresivos más amplios pero increíblemente puntuales, sobre todo en los momentos de mayor lirismo, acompañando apenas con breves expresiones faciales; Muti, que debe conocer indudablemente la Coral de memoria, despliega ante sí, no obstante, la partitura completa de la obra. Acaso afirmando su enfoque literalista y objetivo del Op. 125 del Maestro, a despecho de la enorme emotividad y expresividad de su interpretación; impronta de su acendrada tendencia al virtuosismo. Pero acaso sólo Muti podía ser el virtuoso neo-romántico que extrajera objetívamente de la Coral tan compleja densidad de sensaciones... ¿Las que imaginó, tal vez, el Maestro sordo...? Y el Recitativo, claro... Aquí, un Muti inspiradísimo conduce a la Chicago a una clímax sin precedentes: la potencia del apoteótico movimiento final de la Coral surge, inmaculada, tal vez con el lirismo, la emotividad y la contundencia, que el propio Beethoven hubiese deseado oír. En suma, una ejecución perfecta, de principio a fin. Todo esto, por cierto, gracias al esfuerzo y los dones de un director inspirado, casi en estado de gracia, y un conjunto orquestal, además de los cantantes solistas y el coro, tan finos y perfectos, como poderosos. No sé qué piensan ustedes...

This work does represent the apex of Western Civilization and the Enlightenment Period, with Schiller's poem set to the music of the 4th movement, in which the highest ideals of kindness and beauty are celebrated. Bernstein's Personal life
After much personal struggle and a turbulent on-off engagement, Bernstein married actress Felicia Cohn Montealegre on September 10, 1951. One suggestion is that he chose to marry partly to dispel rumors about his private life to help secure a major conducting appointment, following advice from his mentor Dimitri Mitropoulos about the conservative nature of orchestra boards. In a book released in October 2013, The Leonard Bernstein Letters, his wife acknowledges his homosexuality. Felicia writes: "you are a homosexual and may never change—you don't admit to the possibility of a double life, but if your peace of mind, your health, your whole nervous system depend on a certain sexual pattern what can you do?" Arthur Laurents (Bernstein's collaborator in West Side Story) said that Bernstein was "a gay man who got married. He wasn't conflicted about it at all. He was just gay." Shirley Rhoades Perle, another friend of Bernstein, said that she thought "he required men sexually and women emotionally." But the early years of his marriage seem to have been happy, and no one has suggested Bernstein and his wife did not love each other. They had three children, Jamie, Alexander, and Nina. There are reports, though, that Bernstein did sometimes have brief extramarital liaisons with young men, which several family friends have said his wife knew about. 
A major period of upheaval in Bernstein's personal life began in 1976 when he decided that he could no longer conceal his homosexuality and he left his wife Felicia for a period to live with the musical director of the classical music radio station KKHI-FM in San Francisco, Tom Cothran. The next year Felicia was diagnosed with lung cancer and eventually Bernstein moved back in with her and cared for her until she died on June 16, 1978. Bernstein is reported to have often spoken of his terrible guilt over his wife's death. Most biographies of Bernstein state that his lifestyle became more excessive and his personal behavior sometimes more reckless and crude after her death. However, his public standing and many of his close friendships appear to have remained unaffected, and he resumed his busy schedule of musical activity.
Death and legacy
Bernstein announced his retirement from conducting on October 9, 1990,[49] and died at his apartment at The Dakota of a heart attack five days later, brought on by mesothelioma. He was 72 years old. A longtime heavy smoker, he had emphysema from his mid-50s. On the day of his funeral procession through the streets of Manhattan, construction workers removed their hats and waved, calling out "Goodbye, Lenny." Bernstein is buried in Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York, next to his wife and with a copy of Mahler's Fifth Symphony lying across his heart. On August 25, 2018 (his 100th birthday), he was honored with a Google Doodle.

Thanks for posting, and I did enjoy listening, but it's far from "one of the best renditions".  My key tell for a performance of the 9th is the bassoon parts in the second movement.  They were particularly weak.  Someone else commented on the odd tempos; I too found them jarring.  There is a strange monotonaity, especially obvious in the 3rd.  Is there a splice towards the middle of the third movement?  For a while, everyone is out of tune, then it's better again. I thought the quartet in the chorale lacked chrispness, especially the tenor; I was also a little put off by his tremulo. But I never met a version of the 9th I didn't like, so I'm glad to find this one.

The Unique Story of Beethoven’s Ninth Symphony
Posted on August 2, 2012 by David Nelson
“A grand performance of a new work” is how a prominent Viennese musical newspaper announced a concert of music by Beethoven. Another paper wrote that “anyone whose heart beats warmly for greatness and beauty will surely be present.”

It was on May 7, 1824 that Beethoven’s Ninth Symphony was first performed. The symphony was remarkable for several reasons. It was longer and more complex than any symphony to date and required a larger orchestra. But the most unique feature of “The Ninth” was that Beethoven included chorus and vocal soloists in the final movement. He was the first major composer to do this in a symphony.

Beethoven actually started thinking about setting Friedrich Schiller’s “Ode to Joy” poem to music as early as 1793 when he was 22 years old. Over the following years, the composer would return to this text occasionally and sketch some possible themes for it, but no music was completed. Of course, the “Ode to Joy” has become one of the most recognized melodies in all of music

A Choral Finale


Laimgrubengasse 22 was one the three places Beethoven lived while composing the Ninth Symphony.
In 1817, the Philharmonic Society of London commissioned Beethoven to write a symphony, but he did not start serious work on the new piece until 1822. The first three movements were for the orchestra alone, but the composer knew he needed to end the work with something special. This is when he recalled Schiller’s “Ode to Joy” poem. A movement based on this famous melody was exactly the ending his new symphony needed.

Although it was commissioned by an organization in London, influential Viennese citizens convinced Beethoven to present the first performance in Vienna. The orchestra of the Kärnnertor Theater had to be supplemented with additional musicians, and a chorus of 90 was needed to balance the strength of the orchestra.

Jumping Around Like a Madman

By 1824, Beethoven was almost entirely deaf, but still wanted to be part of the performance and was on stage while the piece was performed to indicate the tempos. Yet, Beethoven could not resist “helping” the musicians on stage by showing them the style and dynamics that he wanted.


The Kaerntnertor Theater in Vienna was where Beethoven’s Ninth was performed for the first time. The theater no longer exists. Today, on the site of the old theater is the Hotel Sacher, right behind the Vienna State Opera House.
The great composer’s actions were animated to say the least. One musician wrote, “he stood in front of the conductor’s stand and threw himself back and forth like a madman. At one moment he stretched to his full height, at the next he crouched down to the floor. He flailed about with his hands and feet as though he wanted to play all the instruments and sing all the chorus parts.” It was a good thing that the conductor had already instructed the musicians not to pay attention to the composer!

Unable to Hear the Applause

Beethoven’s deafness created one of the most touching stories in music. When the symphony was completed, he remained facing the orchestra and could not hear the thunderous applause of the audience for his new symphony. Caroline Unger, the mezzo-soprano soloist, had to tap the deaf composer’s arm and have him turn around so that he could see how the crowd’s response. Many of those in attendance, including Miss Unger, had tears in their eyes when they realized the extent of Beethoven’s deafness.

I guess I should elaborate.  One key to judging a performance of Beethoven's Ninth is the third movement.  Does it hang together structurally?  Are the sonorities balanced?  It's a long and difficult musical meditation, and most conductors get lost in it.  It's an agonizing transition from one kind of music, represented by the conventional, if awesome, first and second movements, which Beethoven thinks he has now exhausted, to an entirely new kind of music, as the male solo goes on to state explicitly.  So it's kinda crucial not to mess it up.  And Wand's third movement is about as convincing as any I have ever heard.

Gwyneth Jones was a magnificent, if erratic, artist. She had a HUGE voice; I saw her live several times and can attest to that fact. Her singing was often wobbly, strident and off-pitch, but when she was in form, it was a gorgeous, warm, all-enveloping sound. She was a very generous singer, and always gave 110%. She sang Fidelio under Bernstein at the Vienna State Opera for the Beethoven bicentenary celebrations in 1970.

Her name is Gwyneth Jones. She actually does mostly Wagnerian operas, not so much lyric soprano stuff. Probably her most well known role was as Brunnhilde in the 1976-1980 Bayreuth production of Wagner's Ring cycle (stage director was Patrice Chereau and conductor was Pierre Boulez). She is still alive, but doesn't really sing anymore (she's 80).

Yeah, it seems that way at first, but it's actually more complex. What conductors do is set the beat and amplify certain pieces of the work or instruments. Some conductors prefer works to be played slowly and place emphasis on strings, horns, etc. Bernstein, for example, prefers fast-paced and, it seems from the second movement, amplified percussion. Conductors spend lots of time studying the sheet music then instruct the orchestra on how to perform their specific interpretation. Compare Bernstein to someone else, and you'll see a huge difference in the how the music is played!

El genio de Ludwig, sumado a todo su dolor y el conjunto de frustraciones que vivió, le permitió, en sordera total, componer una obra sin precedentes en la historia de la música. La profundidad de la melodía, la complejidad de la armonía, la elegancia de la polifonía y la imponencia majestuosa de los coros son la expresión de lo que un ser hombre puede hacer cuando conecta con las Musas y escucha la Música de las Esferas de la que tanto habló Pitágoras de Samos. Cuando Mozart conoció a Beethoven (el primero con más de 30 años y el segundo con al rededor de 17), expresó gran admiración por la capacidad del joven para improvisar, hasta el punto que llegó a decir que 'Ni él mismo podía improvisar de esa manera' y que 'El mundo sabría de él en un futuro'. Haydn, quién fue su profesor de composición, manifestó sentirse superado rápidamente por el genio de su pupilo. Schubert, Verdi, Mendelssohn, Brahms, Rossini, Lizt, Chopin, entre otros genios de la música, profesaban una admiración profunda por el genial sordo alemán que transformó la música de su época. Wagner contó que se desmayó y decidió ser músico después de escuchar la Novena Sinfonía . Dios tenga a Ludwig en su santa gloria. Nuestra deuda estética con él es impagable.

Regreso a mi casa desde mi trabajo y no tengo ganas de hacer nada. Me pongo los audifonos, y empieza el maraton. La Sexta, La Eroica, La Quinta, y La Novena. Y sin darme cuenta le hice de cenar a mi hija, mi esposo y a mis perros, limpie la casa, regué las plantas. También llore muchísimo con La Marcha Funebre de la 3, me alegre con el canto de las aves en la 6 y cante La Oda a la alegría. Beethoven mi compositor favorito, mi amigo al que escucho casi todos los días.

For me, von Karajan interpretation with the Philarmonia orchestra, Chor der  Gessellchaft der Musikfreunde Wien, Elizabeth Schwartzkopf, Häfliger, et. al., recorded in Wien 1955, is the paradigmatic version of Beethoven 9th. The reason is very simple and has nothing to do with musical arcana or technical niceties. This was the first record of the ninth I could buy as a medical student during the early sixties. I heard it I do not know how many times. So THIS version of the 9th became for me THE version of the 9th. I admit the arbitrariness of my decision. One thing that I started thinking from this record   was the problem of the transition from silence to music; I believe the 9th first movement offers a magistral answer to the problem  From the darkness of total silence soft, almost inaudible, gradually increasing sounds that grow until becoming the full blast initial melody. The 4th movement offers the alternative: from total silence to a full blast orchestra tutti. The three initial movements offers so much richness, emotion and beauty has has been overcome by the overplayed 4th movement. Thanks for letting me enjoy for the nth time this wonderful piece of music.

The reprise at 8:00 is like no other. When everything crumbles and the Thing makes its appearance. The opening theme is in major (the third (F#) is in the bass - who would have thought of that in Beethoven's time ?!?), jumping in octaves.
Most conductors try to dramatize what is already dramatic music. They either slow down or try to do something with the music where nothing is necessary. Karajan performs without drama, strict tempo and dynamics. Beethoven has taken care of the drama elements already. Karajan must have felt and understood this otherwise he would not have conducted it in this way.
